.TH RESTORE.SH 1 "2 Jan 2006" "@PACKAGE_VERSION@" "@PACKAGE_NAME@ utils"

.SH NAME
restore.sh \- restore an entire backed up directory

.SH SYNOPSIS
.B restore.sh
[
.IR OPTIONS
]
.IR BACKUPDIR
[
.IR DIR
]

.SH DESCRIPTION
\fBrestore.sh\fR restores an entire backed up directory (recusively) to
another directory. This allows one to return to a previous state of a
filesystem. 
.PP
By default \fBrestore.sh\fR will restore to the last backed up state,
i.e the file you'll get when you run `yesterday.sh' without options.
.PP
Backed up files will be copied as-is, not unzipping are decryption will 
be attempted.

.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.B \-b backupdir
Alternate backup directory. Defaults to /vol/backup/`hostname`.
.TP
.B \-n daysago
Select the dump daysago prior to the current day.

.SH FILES
Root of the dump file system defaults to /vol/backup/`hostname`, but can
be any location.

.SH SEE ALSO
diff(1), hist.sh(1), yesterday(1) and rdup(8)
